{"timestamp": "2025-12-07 05:24:31.341155", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\\n\\nSummary\\n- The network is partially degraded. All services are healthy and reachable from the 10.2.1.0/24 access domain (behind router_dist_2_1), including DNS and the web/load-balancer farm (10.200.0.0/24).\\n- The 10.1.1.0/24 access domain (behind router_dist_1_1) is isolated: hosts are not getting IP addresses via DHCP and have no IP connectivity to the server farm.\\n- Root causes:\\n  1) FRR/OSPF is down on router_core_1, breaking OSPF adjacency with router_dist_1_1 and isolating that distribution domain from the core/server farm.\\n  2) The DHCP relay on router_dist_1_1 is not running, preventing DHCP requests in 10.1.1.0/24 from reaching the central DHCP server.\\n\\nObserved Symptoms and Evidence\\n1) Host-level symptoms\\n- host_1_1_1_1 (10.1.1.0/24):\\n  - No IP address configured; only link-layer present.\\n    Evidence: get_host_net_config shows eth0 up but no IPv4 address; ip route is empty; pings from this host fail with “Network is unreachable”.\\n  - curl to web99.local returns near-zero timing placeholders (local failure), consistent with no IP stack configured.\\n\\n- host_2_1_1_1 (10.2.1.0/24):\\n  - Has a DHCP-assigned address 10.2.1.25/24 with default route via 10.2.1.1.\\n    Evidence: ip addr shows “dynamic eth0 valid_lft ~58sec”; ip route has “default via 10.2.1.1”.\\n  - Can ping DNS (10.200.0.2), load_balancer (10.200.0.7), and web servers (10.200.0.3–.6).\\n  - HTTP tests succeed:\\n    • curl http://web99.local returns total times ~1.0–1.1 s (DNS resolves, HTTP LB reachable).\\n    • curl http://web0.local returns total times ~1.0 s (frontend web service reachable).\\n\\n2) Distribution routers\\n- router_dist_1_1 (serves 10.1.1.0/24):\\n  - OSPF running but no neighbors and no OSPF-learned routes beyond local links.\\n    Evidence:\\n    • vtysh “show ip ospf neighbor” shows header only (no neighbors).\\n    • vtysh “show ip route” has only connected 10.1.1.0/24 and the P2P 172.16.0.6/31.\\n  - IP connectivity on uplink is fine at L3 (can ping its P2P neighbor address 172.16.0.6), but cannot reach server farm addresses (no routes).\\n  - DHCP relay process is not running.\\n    Evidence: systemctl status isc-dhcp-relay → “inactive (dead)”.\\n  - Attempts to ping dhcp_server (10.200.0.8) result in “Network is unreachable” due to missing routes from failed OSPF adjacency.\\n\\n- router_dist_2_1 (serves 10.2.1.0/24):\\n  - OSPF is healthy.\\n    Evidence:\\n    • FRR active.\\n    • OSPF neighbor with core via 172.16.0.14/31 in Full state.\\n    • IP routing table contains OSPF-learned routes including 10.200.0.0/24 via core.\\n  - Note: systemctl status isc-dhcp-relay also shows “inactive (dead)” on this node, but hosts in 10.2.1.0/24 are obtaining DHCP leases successfully. This suggests relay functionality is being provided elsewhere (or via a different mechanism/service name) in this lab environment for this segment. Regardless, DHCP is working in 10.2.1.0/24.\\n\\n3) Core and server-access routing\\n- router_core_1:\\n  - FRR service is not running.\\n    Evidence: systemctl status frr → “inactive (dead)”.\\n  - All core-facing interfaces have IPs, but no routing daemon is advertising/learning routes.\\n\\n- router_core_2 and router_core_3:\\n  - FRR active, OSPF adjacencies are up and in Full state with peers (core and server-access).\\n  - Functioning OSPF backbone for the rest of the network.\\n\\n- server_access_router:\\n  - FRR active, OSPF neighbor with core3 in Full state.\\n  - Server farm (10.200.0.0/24) reachable from healthy access domain (10.2.1.0/24).\\n\\nAnomalies Detected\\n- Critical: FRR/OSPF down on router_core_1. This prevents router_dist_1_1 (10.1.1.0/24) from joining the OSPF domain and learning routes to the server farm/DNS/DHCP.\\n- Critical: DHCP relay not running on router_dist_1_1. Hosts in 10.1.1.0/24 cannot obtain DHCP leases, leaving them without IP configuration.\\n\\nLocalization of Faults\\n- router_core_1: OSPF control plane failure (FRR inactive).\\n- router_dist_1_1: DHCP relay process inactive. Also isolated from OSPF core due to the core1 issue.\\n\\nRoot Cause Analysis\\n- Primary control-plane root cause for 10.1.1.0/24 isolation: FRR/OSPF is down on router_core_1, which is the only uplink neighbor for router_dist_1_1. Without OSPF on core1, router_dist_1_1 has no neighbor adjacency and no routes to 10.200.0.0/24 (or the broader network), rendering DHCP relays and server access impossible from that domain.\\n- Immediate service root cause for host 10.1.1.0/24 IP failure: DHCP relay is not running on router_dist_1_1, so even if the routing were up, DHCP requests would not reach the central DHCP server.\\n\\nScope of Impact\\n- Affected: All user hosts behind router_dist_1_1 (10.1.1.0/24). They cannot obtain IP addresses via DHCP and cannot reach DNS or the server farm.\\n- Not affected: User hosts behind router_dist_2_1 (10.2.1.0/24). They obtain DHCP leases and successfully reach the server farm and web services through OSPF via core2/core3.\\n\\nAdditional Notes\\n- DNS service appears healthy (hosts in 10.2.1.0/24 resolve and access web services normally).\\n- Web services and the load balancer in 10.200.0.0/24 function correctly from the healthy domain.\\n- The short DHCP lease timers (default 30s, max 60s) are unusual but consistent across the lab and do not indicate a fault by themselves., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='e95a7c54-d4f2-44cc-a367-a03ff94bea46'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
